On 11/05/2018 02:43 PM, Ben Greenfield via TUHS wrote:
> I found that I had to do all of this using SASL.

At first read I was thinking "SASL?  Really?".  Then I remembered that=20
Simple Authentication and Security Layer is really just an abstraction=20
layer.  An abstraction layer that very easily could have (but I don't=20
know one way or the other) a back end to Kerberos.

> I remember it as SASL would handle the kerberization during boot up=20
> getting tickets for each LDAP entry that you wanted mapped to a service=
=20
> on that client.

Hum.

> I could be wrong but I think SASL seems to be way connect services on=20
> Linux with LDAP that are served kerberized.

I've always viewed SASL as a way for applications to outsource the=20
authentication / security so that the program code didn't need to worry=20
about it.  It also allowed SASL to manage supporting all the different=20
back end security methods.

I also think much the same about PAM.  -  In fact, I don't think I could =

properly differentiate between PAM and SASL.



--=20
Grant. . . .
